Wow, good job! This is quite a 3D game! Few performance tips for you. In the `Player.prototype.cockpit` function, you seem to do ```var img = get();
ctx.image(img, 0, 0, ctx.width, ctx.height);
```
which is later used for ```//Targeting screen
fill(0, 0, 0);
quad(234, 316, 369, 316, 362, 379, 242, 379);
image(ctx, 250, 325, 100, 50);
```
You can change the `ctx` to `img` instead and delete the `ctx` stuff. it will make your program significantly faster(for me from 30 fps to 38). In the line```stroke(blue(get(300, 200)) > 50 ? -16711847 : -65536);```
you are using get to get the color value of a single pixel. In this case you can check for `imageData` instead```stroke(imageData.data[(300 + 200 * width) * 4 + 3] > 50 ? -16711847 : -65536);``` and that should make it faster(from 38 fps to 48). In the `Asteroids.prototype.checkCollide`, you're doing```return Math.hypot(
    pos[0] - this.position[0],
    pos[1] - this.position[1],
    pos[2] - this.position[2]
) < r + this.r;
```
But since you are not getting the distance, you can square both sides and remove the slow square root operation. The code looks like this, ```var x = pos[0] - this.position[0];
var y = pos[1] - this.position[1];
var z = pos[2] - this.position[2];
var radius = r + this.r;
return x * x + y * y + z * z < radius * radius;
```
This will make the fps from 48 to 60. Those are the low hanging fruits. There are others like remove the `loadPixels` by making the gradient with loops and drawing the stars with ```var l = (x + y * width) * 4;
data[l] = 255;
data[l + 1] = 255;
data[l + 2] = 255;
```
but that requires some surgery to the code so I won't describe them in deatails.
